    <h2>What Financiers Look For</h2>

    <p>
      Getting approved for capital equipment financing in Malaysia isn't as tough as getting a bank loan — but you still need to show you're a safe bet. Here's what matters:
    </p>

    <h3>1. Business Track Record</h3>
    <p>
      Most financiers want <strong>at least 2 years of operating history</strong>. Startups can qualify if they have strong pre-orders or contracts showing the equipment will generate revenue.
    </p>

    <h3>2. Cash Flow</h3>
    <p>
      Can your business afford the monthly payment? They'll review your bank statements and profit & loss to ensure you have consistent revenue.
    </p>

    <h3>3. Equipment Details</h3>
    <p>
      What are you buying, and from whom? Reputable suppliers and well-known brands (Okuma, Haas, Mitsubishi) get faster approvals. Custom or obscure equipment may face more scrutiny.
    </p>

    <h3>4. Down Payment Ability</h3>
    <p>
      Can you put down 10-30%? A larger down payment reduces the financier's risk and may unlock better rates.
    </p>

    <h3>5. Collateral (Sometimes)</h3>
    <p>
      The equipment itself is collateral. But if the asset is highly specialized (limited resale value), they may ask for additional security — property, director's guarantee, or corporate guarantee.
    </p>

    <h2>Common Mistakes (And How to Avoid Them)</h2>

    <h3>❌ Buying Equipment Before Securing Financing</h3>
    <p>
      Get approval <em>first</em>. If financing falls through, you're stuck with a supplier invoice you can't pay.
    </p>

    <h3>❌ Ignoring Total Cost of Ownership</h3>
    <p>
      A RM600,000 machine with 8% interest over 5 years costs RM888,000 total. Factor in maintenance, spare parts, and operator training too.
    </p>

    <h3>❌ Choosing the Cheapest Rate Without Reading Terms</h3>
    <p>
      A 4.5% rate with a 2-year balloon payment is riskier than a 6% rate with predictable monthly installments. Read the fine print.
    </p>

    <h3>❌ Overestimating Revenue Impact</h3>
    <p>
      Be realistic. That new CNC machine won't double your orders overnight. Budget for a ramp-up period.
    </p>

    <h2>Is Capital Equipment Financing Right for You?</h2>

    <p><strong>Good fit if:</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>You need equipment that costs RM200,000+</li>
      <li>The asset will directly generate revenue or cut production costs</li>
      <li>You want to preserve working capital for operations</li>
      <li>Your business has stable cash flow (even if not huge)</li>
    </ul>

    <p><strong>Not ideal if:</strong></p>
    <ul>
