    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <h3>What's the difference between capital equipment and operational equipment?</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>Capital equipment</strong> is used to <em>make products</em> — like production lines, CNC machines, and industrial ovens. <strong>Operational equipment</strong> supports day-to-day operations — like forklifts, office computers, and delivery vans. Capital equipment usually costs more and lasts longer (7-15 years).
    </p>

    <h3>Can startups get capital equipment financing?</h3>
    <p>
      Yes, but it's harder. You'll need strong business plans, pre-orders, or contracts proving the equipment will generate revenue. A larger down payment (30-40%) also helps. Established businesses (2+ years) get better rates and terms.
    </p>

    <h3>What if the equipment breaks down?</h3>
    <p>
      You still owe the monthly payment — financing doesn't cover repairs. That's why many businesses budget for <strong>maintenance contracts</strong> or <strong>equipment insurance</strong> when financing major assets.
    </p>

    <h3>Can I pay off the loan early?</h3>
    <p>
      Usually yes, but check for <strong>prepayment penalties</strong>. Some financiers charge a fee (1-3% of remaining balance) for early payoff. Others allow free early repayment after 12-24 months.
    </p>

    <h3>What happens if I can't make a payment?</h3>
    <p>
      Missing payments damages your credit and may lead to asset repossession. If you're facing cash flow issues, <strong>talk to your financier immediately</strong>. Many will restructure terms or offer temporary payment relief rather than repossess equipment.
    </p>

    <h3>Do I need perfect credit?</h3>
    <p>
      No. Unlike banks, many equipment financiers focus on <strong>cash flow and asset value</strong> rather than credit scores. Even businesses with past credit issues can qualify if they show stable revenue and a clear use case for the equipment.
    </p>

